<section class="ownership-map" aria-label="Relationship between shareholder, share, corporation, and business">
  <p class="exercise__label">Ownership relationship map</p>
  <div class="ownership-map__flow">
    <article>
      <span>1 · You</span>
      <strong>Shareholder</strong>
      <small>Contribute capital and hold rights</small>
    </article>
    <div class="ownership-map__arrow"><b>own</b><span>shares</span></div>
    <article class="ownership-map__share">
      <span>2 · Your security</span>
      <strong>Share</strong>
      <small>A residual claim and attached voting rights</small>
    </article>
    <div class="ownership-map__arrow"><b>is a claim on</b><span>the legal entity</span></div>
    <article class="ownership-map__corporation">
      <span>3 · Legal container</span>
      <strong>Corporation</strong>
      <small>Owns assets, signs contracts, owes debts, pays taxes</small>
    </article>
    <div class="ownership-map__arrow"><b>owns and operates</b><span>the economic system</span></div>
    <article class="ownership-map__business">
      <span>4 · Productive activity</span>
      <strong>Business</strong>
      <small>Serves customers, employs people, competes, and earns cash</small>
    </article>
  </div>

  <div class="ownership-map__restaurant">
    <strong>Restaurant example</strong>
    <div>
      <span><b>Corporation:</b> Seattle Dinner, Inc.</span>
      <span><b>Business:</b> taking reservations, cooking meals, serving guests, and earning revenue</span>
      <span><b>Assets owned by corporation:</b> cash, ovens, lease rights, brand, and contracts</span>
      <span><b>Your property:</b> 10 shares of Seattle Dinner, Inc.—not its oven or bank account</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="ownership-map__test">
    <strong>The transfer test</strong>
    <p>
      If Seattle Dinner, Inc. sells the restaurant operation to Buyer Corp., the
      <em>business</em> may keep serving the same customers, but it now sits inside a different
      <em>corporation</em>. Your shares still claim Seattle Dinner, Inc., which now owns the sale
      proceeds—not the restaurant operation.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
